Exploratory Data Analysis of BHP Group (2005–2025)¶

This project analyzes the long-term performance of BHP Group Limited (ASX: BHP), one of the world’s largest mining companies.
The dataset consists of monthly stock price history from Jan 2005 to Aug 2025.

The goals of this analysis are to:

  • Summarize BHP’s long-term returns and growth (CAGR).
  • Examine price trends and link them to major global events.
  • Measure risk through volatility and drawdowns.
  • Explore long- vs short-term cycles using moving averages.

Company Overview

BHP Group Limited (BHP) is a diversified natural resources company. It is engaged in mining of copper, silver, zinc, molybdenum, uranium and gold, iron ore, metallurgical coal and energy coal.

Principal Activity

Exploration, development and production of oil and gas; Mining of iron ore, metallurgical coal and energy coal, copper, silver, zinc, molybdenum, uranium and gold.

*Dataset Timeframe and Source*

Monthly Price History Jan 31st 2005 - August 29th 2025, sourced from DataAnalysis Premium

*Known Big Key Events*

2008 GFC, 2015 commodity crash, 2020 COVID, 2021 rally

Case Study¶

How do global commodity cycles affect the financial and stock performance of BHP?

Executive Summary¶

BHP has grown steadily over the past 20 years (CAGR ~6%), but its performance is highly cyclical, with volatility and drawdowns closely tied to global commodity market shocks.

1. Descriptive Statistics¶

To understand BHP’s long-term performance, a statistics summary is calculated for the stock’s closing price, as well as the Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) from 2005–2025.

  • CAGR tells us the steady annualized rate of growth (or decline) over the entire 20-year period.
  • Along with min, max, mean, and standard deviation, this gives a baseline picture of BHP’s stock performance.
In [638]:
df = cb.get_data()
print(f"""'Close' Col. Summary Stats (to 2DP):
    Min: {round(df['Close'].min(),2)}
    Max: {round(df['Close'].max(),2)}
    Mean: {round(df['Close'].mean(),2)}
    Median: {round(df['Close'].median(),2)}
    Std Dev: {round(df['Close'].std(),2)}  
     """)

# CAGR Value | 2005 - 2025 CAGR %
last_price = df["Close"].iloc[0]
first_price = df["Close"].iloc[-1]
year_difference = 2025 - 2005 + 7/12
CAGR = (last_price / first_price) ** (1/year_difference) - 1
print(f"First price (31/1/2005): {first_price} | Last price (29/8/2025): {last_price}")
print(f"2005-2025 GACR Rate: {round(CAGR * 100, 2)}%")

# GACR Rate Sanity Check
print("\nGACR Rate Sanity Check")

predicted_last = first_price * ((1+CAGR))** year_difference
print("Actual Last Price: " + str(last_price))
print("Predicted Last Price: " + str(round(predicted_last, 2)))

df["Monthly Returns"] = df["Close"].pct_change()

monthly_returns_min = df["Monthly Returns"].min()
monthly_returns_max = df["Monthly Returns"].max()
monthly_returns_mean = df["Monthly Returns"].mean()
monthly_returns_stdev = df["Monthly Returns"].std()

min_index = df.index[df["Monthly Returns"] == monthly_returns_min][0]
max_index = df.index[df["Monthly Returns"] == monthly_returns_max][0]
min_date = df.loc[min_index, "Date"]
max_date = df.loc[max_index, "Date"]

print("'Monthly Returns' Col. Summary Stats:\n"
        f"Worst Return: {monthly_returns_min:.2%} | {min_date}\n"
        f"Best Return: {monthly_returns_max:.2%} | {max_date}\n"
        f"Average Return: {monthly_returns_mean:.2%}\n"
        f"Std. Dev. Return: {monthly_returns_stdev:.2%}")

Descriptive Statistics Conclusion

Over the 20-year period (2005–2025), BHP’s stock price grew from $13.13 to $43.19, achieving a steady Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) of ~6%.
The price ranged between a low of $12.94 and a high of $50.41, with an average value near $30 and a standard deviation of $8.41, highlighting significant long-term volatility.

Monthly returns underline this cyclicality: the worst monthly loss was –18.5% (March 2016) during the commodity downturn, while the best monthly gain was +33.6% (August 2008) at the peak of the resource boom.
On average, monthly returns were slightly negative (–0.22%), reflecting the fact that gains came in sharp cycles rather than in smooth, incremental increases.

Taken together, these statistics show that while BHP delivered meaningful long-term growth, it did so through a volatile path marked by sharp booms and deep downturns.

2. Volatility and Price Analysis¶

BHP’s stock price shows a cyclical pattern over the 2005–2025 period, with sharp rises followed by deep declines. Volatility, measured as the 12-month rolling standard deviation of returns, clearly spikes around major global and commodity-related events.

  • 2008 (Global Financial Crisis): Price dropped sharply, with volatility reaching its highest point of the period.
  • 2015 (Commodity downturn): Both price and returns became highly unstable, marking another major stress event.
  • 2020 (COVID shock): Volatility surged again as global markets sold off, but was followed by a strong rebound.
  • 2021 (Commodity rally): Price hit new highs, while volatility tapered off as markets stabilized.

Overall, the analysis shows that BHP’s performance is tightly linked to global macroeconomic cycles. Prices tend to recover strongly after downturns, but volatility consistently spikes during crises — reinforcing that long-term growth has come with significant short-term risk.

3. Drawdowns¶

The largest drawdown in BHP’s stock price over 2005–2025 occurred between March 2011 and January 2016, where the stock fell by 63.6% (from 37.56 to 13.67).

This downturn coincided with the collapse in global commodity prices, particularly iron ore and coal, as demand from China slowed.

BHP did not fully recover its 2011 peak until December 2020, showing that investors endured nearly a decade-long drawdown period.

This highlights the cyclicality of resource companies. Strong booms are often followed by extended busts before recovery.

In [648]:
df = df.sort_values("Date").reset_index(drop=True)

df["Peak"] = df["Close"].cummax()
df["Drawdown"] = (df["Close"] - df["Peak"]) / df["Peak"]

# Trough (worst point)
trough_idx = df["Drawdown"].idxmin()
trough_date = df.loc[trough_idx, "Date"]
trough_price = df.loc[trough_idx, "Close"]
worst_drawdown = df.loc[trough_idx, "Drawdown"]

# Peak before trough
peak_idx = df.loc[:trough_idx, "Close"].idxmax()
peak_date = df.loc[peak_idx, "Date"]
peak_price = df.loc[peak_idx, "Close"]

recovery = df.loc[trough_idx:, "Close"] >= peak_price
if recovery.any():
    recovery_idx = recovery.idxmax()
    recovery_date = df.loc[recovery_idx, "Date"]
else:
    recovery_date = None

print(f"Max Drawdown: {worst_drawdown:.2%}")
print(f"From {peak_date.date()} (${peak_price:.2f}) "
      f"to {trough_date.date()} (${trough_price:.2f})")
if recovery_date:
    print(f"Recovered by {recovery_date.date()}")
else:
    print("Not yet recovered")

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
plt.plot(df["Date"], df["Close"], label="Monthly Close", color="#0A174E")

# Shade drawdown region
plt.axvspan(peak_date, trough_date, color="red", alpha=0.2, label="Max Drawdown")

# Highlight peak & trough points
plt.scatter(peak_date, peak_price, color="green", marker="^", s=100, label="Peak")
plt.scatter(trough_date, trough_price, color="red", marker="v", s=100, label="Trough")

plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Stock Price ($)")
plt.title("BHP: Monthly Closing Price with Max Drawdown Highlighted")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

4. 📊 Moving Averages (12M vs 36M)¶

To identify medium- and long-term stock trends, a 12-month moving average (MA12) and a 36-month moving average (MA36) were calculated.

  • Golden Cross (green triangle): occurs when the short-term MA12 crosses above the long-term MA36, often viewed as a bullish (positive) signal.
  • Death Cross (red triangle): occurs when MA12 crosses below MA36, often viewed as a bearish (negative) signal.

Observations:¶

  • A golden cross was observed in 2009, coinciding with the recovery after the Global Financial Crisis.
  • Multiple death crosses occurred in 2012 and 2015, aligning with commodity downturns.
  • Another golden cross appeared in 2017, ahead of BHP’s strong recovery into the 2020s.
  • Most recently, a death cross in 2024 suggests weakening momentum as commodity prices cooled.

Conclusion:¶

Moving averages successfully captured BHP’s cyclical nature — long rallies often ended with death crosses, while recoveries tended to start with golden crosses. However, like all technical signals, these patterns should be interpreted alongside fundamentals (e.g., commodity prices, global demand).

In [651]:
df["MA12"] = df["Close"].rolling(window=12).mean()   # 12-month
df["MA36"] = df["Close"].rolling(window=36).mean()   # 36-month
df["Crossover"] = df["MA12"] - df["MA36"]

golden = df[(df["Crossover"] > 0) & (df["Crossover"].shift(1) <= 0)]

death = df[(df["Crossover"] < 0) & (df["Crossover"].shift(1) >= 0)]
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
plt.plot(df["Date"], df["Close"], label="Monthly Close", color="#0A174E")
plt.plot(df["Date"], df["MA12"], label="12M Moving Average", color="#FF9F1C")
plt.plot(df["Date"], df["MA36"], label="36M Moving Average", color="#2EC4B6")

plt.scatter(golden["Date"], golden["MA12"], marker="^", color="green", s=100, label="Golden Cross")
plt.scatter(death["Date"], death["MA12"], marker="v", color="red", s=100, label="Death Cross")

plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Stock Price ($)")
plt.title("BHP: Closing Price with 12M & 36M Moving Averages + Crossovers")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Final Conclusion¶

Over the 2005–2025 period, BHP’s stock demonstrated steady long-term growth (CAGR ~6%), but this came with periods of intense volatility and sharp drawdowns.

  • Descriptive statistics showed a strong overall performance, with the price rising from ~$13 in 2005 to ~$43 in 2025, despite an average monthly return close to zero.
  • Trend analysis highlighted clear links between global events (2008 GFC, 2015 commodity crash, 2020 COVID shock, and 2021 rally) and price movements.
  • Volatility analysis revealed that major spikes in risk consistently aligned with these crises, showing BHP’s exposure to global commodity cycles.
  • Drawdowns quantified the impact of downturns — the largest, from 2011 to 2016, wiped out more than 60% of value before full recovery in 2020.
  • Moving averages confirmed BHP’s cyclical nature, with golden and death crosses marking transitions between growth and decline phases.

Advise¶

BHP’s long-term growth has rewarded investors, but its performance is highly cyclical, strongly tied to global commodity markets. The stock is prone to sharp downturns during global crises but has consistently recovered over time. For investors, this highlights the importance of long-term holding horizons* and awareness of commodity-driven risks.
